    <Folder>
      <name>Intelligence Summary</name>
      <Placemark>
        <name>AI Council Assessment</name>
        <styleUrl>#intel</styleUrl>
        <description>The synthesized intelligence reveals a military posture characterized by elevated operational readiness across multiple theaters, with particular emphasis on countering Iranian aggression in the Gulf of Oman and deterring Chinese expansionism in the South China Sea and Luzon Strait. The USS Abraham Lincoln carrier strike group is actively enforcing a blockade against Iranian vessels in the Gulf of Oman, following recent strikes on Iranian-flagged ships attempting to breach sanctions, while the USS John C. Stennis operates in the Philippine Sea as part of broader regional deterrence efforts. Amphibious ready groups, including USS Wasp and USS America, are forward-deployed in the South China Sea, participating in joint exercises with Philippine and Japanese forces that culminated in anti-ship missile drills. Domestically, carrier groups such as USS Gerald R. Ford and USS Nimitz are undergoing maintenance, indicating a rotation strategy to maintain global presence. The data also highlights expanded special operations support, with CH-47 Chinooks and MH-60 Seahawks likely engaged in rapid deployment and maritime ISR missions. The resumption of F-14 Tomcat operations, even in a museum context, suggests a potential revival of legacy platforms for training or symbolic deterrence. Overall, the military posture reflects a dual-focus strategy: enforcing maritime security in the Middle East while maintaining a robust deterrent presence in the Indo-Pacific, with rapid deployment capabilities and expanded special operations support as key pillars of readiness.</description>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>0,0,0</coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
